  "response": "Capgemini generally has a business casual dress code. However, the specific interpretation can vary slightly between different offices and teams. Here's a breakdown of what's generally considered acceptable for fresher girls at Capgemini:\n\n**Generally Accepted:**\n\n*   **Tops:**\n    *   Blouses: Solid colors, subtle prints, or patterns. Avoid anything too low-cut or revealing.\n    *   Shirts: Collared shirts, polo shirts (especially on casual Fridays).\n    *   Sweaters: Cardigans, pullovers, or sweater vests (worn over blouses or shirts).\n    *   T-shirts: Plain, professional-looking t-shirts, especially on casual Fridays. Avoid graphic tees with large logos or slogans.\n*   **Bottoms:**\n    *   Trousers: Formal trousers in neutral colors (black, navy, gray, beige, brown).\n    *   Skirts: Knee-length or slightly below. Pencil skirts or A-line skirts are good choices.\n    *   Dresses: Knee-length or slightly below. Modest dresses that are not too revealing.\n*   **Shoes:**\n    *   Closed-toe shoes are generally preferred.\n    *   Flats: Ballet flats, loafers, or other comfortable flats.\n    *   Heels: Low to medium heels (avoid overly high or flashy heels).\n    *   Boots: Ankle boots or knee-high boots can be acceptable, depending on the office and weather.\n*   **Outerwear:**\n    *   Blazers: A great way to dress up any outfit.\n    *   Cardigans: For layering and adding warmth.\n    *   Jackets: Professional-looking jackets.\n*   **Accessories:**\n    *   Simple jewelry: Earrings, necklaces, bracelets, rings.\n    *   Scarves: Can add a pop of color or pattern to an outfit.\n    *   Watches: A professional accessory.\n    *   Handbags: Professional-looking handbags or tote bags.\n\n**Things to Avoid (Generally):**\n\n*   **Extremely Casual Clothing:**\n    *   Jeans: Generally, jeans are not acceptable for freshers unless it's specifically designated \"Casual Friday\" and confirmed by your team.\n    *   Shorts\n    *   Leggings (worn as pants)\n    *   Sweatpants\n    *   Hoodies (unless part of a specifically approved company-branded item)\n*   **Revealing Clothing:**\n    *   Low-cut tops\n    *   Spaghetti straps\n    *   Mini skirts\n    *   Sheer clothing\n*   **Distracting Clothing:**\n    *   Clothing with large logos or slogans\n    *   Bright neon colors\n    *   Ripped or distressed clothing\n*   **Uncomfortable or Impractical Shoes:**\n    *   Very high heels\n    *   Flip-flops\n    *   Sneakers (unless specifically allowed on Casual Friday)\n\n**Tips for Fresher Girls:**\n\n*   **Observe:** During your first few days, pay attention to what other employees are wearing, especially those in your team or department. This will give you a good sense of the specific dress code in your office.\n*   **Ask Your Manager or HR:** If you're unsure about anything, don't hesitate to ask your manager or HR representative for clarification. It's better to be safe than sorry.\n*   **Err on the Side of Formal:** When in doubt, it's always better to dress a little more formally than to be underdressed.\n*   **Comfort is Key:** Choose clothing and shoes that are comfortable to wear all day. You'll be spending a lot of time at your desk and in meetings, so you want to be able to focus on your work, not your discomfort.\n*   **Be Professional:** Your clothing should reflect your professionalism and respect for your workplace.\n\n**Casual Friday:**\n\n*   If your office has a \"Casual Friday,\" you may be able to wear jeans, sneakers, and more relaxed tops. However, it's still important to maintain a professional appearance. Avoid anything too casual or revealing, even on Casual Friday.\n\n**Disclaimer:**  This information is based on general guidelines and common practices. Always check with your specific Capgemini office or team for their specific dress code policies.  The best approach is to observe and ask when in doubt.\n",
